         <h1>R. M. Hare, British Philosopher, Dies at 82; Looked for Logic in Morals </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>R.M. Hare , a moral philosopher who wrestled ethical questions out of the murky realm of emotion and into the hard-edged arena of logic , died on Jan. 29 in his home in Ewelme , England . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 82 . <br><blue>3</blue>Professor Hare had suffered a number of strokes in recent years , his son , John , said . <br><blue>4</blue>One of the pre-eminent moral philosophers of the postwar era , he wrote the classic book '' The Language of Morals '' ( 1952 ) , taught for nearly four decades at Oxford University and was later graduate research professor emeritus at the University of Florida . <br><blue>5</blue>Moral philosophy , which preoccupied thinkers from Socrates on , aims to answer the question : What is the essential form and function of ethical statements ? <br><blue>6</blue>Professor Hare sought an answer by peeling back the surface of everyday moral statements -- '' I should not cheat my employer , '' '' I ought to give to the poor '' -- to reveal the logical infrastructure below . '' <br><blue>7</blue>My life 's ambition , '' he once said , was '' to find a way of answering moral questions rationally . '' <br><blue>8</blue>In the first half of the 20th century , moral philosophy was more concerned with feeling . <br><blue>9</blue>A dominant school , called emotivism , viewed ethical propositions as simple mirrors of emotional states . <br><blue>10</blue>As such , the emotivists said , they reflected speakers ' inward feelings , like disapproval ( of cheating ) or approbation ( of generosity ) . <br><blue>11</blue>But to some philosophers , emotivism was facile and subjective , trafficking in unverifiable speculation ; critics called it the '' Boo-Hooray '' theory of morality . <br><blue>12</blue>How , they asked , could an utterance be proved beyond doubt to be a window to the impenetrable landscape of interior states ? <br><blue>13</blue>What was needed , they argued , was an objective method of unknotting the tangled logic of moral questions . <br><blue>14</blue>Professor Hare devised one . <br><blue>15</blue>Combining the linguistic analysis of the philosopher J. L. Austin with Kant 's idea of the categorical imperative ( the injunction to behave as if one 's actions were universal law ) , he developed a theory of morality that set forth two essential properties of moral statements : First , a moral statement is prescriptive , functioning not as a barometer of emotional weather but as an actual declaration of behavior , committing the speaker to a pragmatic course of action , like behaving honestly or giving to charity . <br><blue>16</blue>Second , a moral proposition is universalizable , or an instance of a larger truth ( like the general concept of charity as a virtue ) that applies to virtually everyone . <br><blue>17</blue>Professor Hare 's theory , known as prescriptivism , dominated moral philosophy in the 1950 's and 60 's . <br><blue>18</blue>Richard Mervyn Hare was born March 21 , 1919 , in Backwell , England . <br><blue>19</blue>While studying at Oxford in the late 1930 's , he agonized over whether to enlist or declare himself a pacifist as war loomed in Europe . <br><blue>20</blue>It was a choice , he would later say , that helped direct him toward moral philosophy . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>they</m_str> (10_8) 	<m_str>the emotivists</m_str> (10_4) 	<br><blue>2(1)</blue>: <m_str>a moral proposition</m_str> (16_3) 	<br><blue>3(1)</blue>: <m_str>Oxford</m_str> (19_4) 	<br><blue>4(20)</blue>: <m_str>his</m_str> (3_13) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (6_26) 	<m_str>his son , John</m_str> (3_13) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (19_11) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (4_12) 	<m_str>himself</m_str> (19_19) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (20_6) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (15_34) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (20_14) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Professor Hare 's</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>Professor Hare</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_31) 	<m_str>Professor Hare</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>Professor Hare</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>Richard Mervyn Har